I like `String.StartsWith()` because of it's readability and I want to keep in my code. Therefore I don't post this suggestion in the analyzer section.

Any call to String.StartsWith with a single constant character string en `StringComparison.Ordinal` can be lowered to code like this:
```csharp
// assume value is the string
// assume c is the first character of constant character string
ArgumentNullException.ThrowIfNull(value);
if (value.Length == 0) return false;
return value[0] == c;
```
I hooked this up in an extension method:
```csharp
public static bool StartsWithOrdinal(this string value, char c)
{
	ArgumentNullException.ThrowIfNull(value);
	if (value.Length == 0) return false;
	return value[0] == c;
}
```
and ran a benchmark:

```csharp
[Benchmark(Baseline = true)]
public bool Orginal()
{
	return TestValue.StartsWith("@", StringComparison.Ordinal);
}

[Benchmark]
public bool Modified()
{
	return TestValue.StartsWithOrdinal('@');
}
```

|      Method |      Mean |     Error |    StdDev | Ratio |
|------------ |----------:|----------:|----------:|------:|
| Orginal | 3.8787 ns | 0.1021 ns | 0.0852 ns | 1.000 |
|    Modified| 0.0391 ns | 0.0337 ns | 0.0375 ns | 0.009 |

(I did get a warning:  'The method duration is indistinguishable from the empty method duration')

This method can be used for multicharacter strings also, but at a given time you're generating to much code and lossing performance. 

An example for checking if a string starts with 'https://' in ordinal ignore case:
```csharp
// assume value is the string
ArgumentNullException.ThrowIfNull(value);
if (value.Length < 8) return false;
if (value[0] is not ('H' or 'h')) return false;
if (value[1] is not ('T' or 't')) return false;
if (value[2] is not ('T' or 't')) return false;
if (value[3] is not ('P' or 'p')) return false;
if (value[4] is not ('S' or 's')) return false;
if (value[5] is not ':') return false;
if (value[6] is not '/') return false;
if (value[7] is not '/') return false;
return true;
```
This is over 2 times faster than a regular call to `String.StartsWith("https://", StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase)` but it also increases code size a lot. On the other hand the compiler has access to the internal working of the String object and could generate a much faster vector based comparison, like StartsWith uses internally.

